      "type": "answer",
      "text": "## Enterprise Root Cause Analysis: WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR\n\n### Stop Code: 0x00000124\n\n---\n\n### 1. Root Cause Analysis (5-Why Method)\n\n| Level | Question | Answer |\n|-------|----------|--------|\n| **Why 1** | Why did the system crash? | Windows detected an uncorrectable hardware error via WHEA framework |\n| **Why 2** | Why was the error uncorrectable? | Hardware component exceeded error correction capabilities (MCA registers) |\n| **Why 3** | Why did the hardware fail? | Likely causes: overheating, unstable overclock, failing RAM/CPU, voltage instability, or faulty drivers |\n| **Why 4** | Why did this happen repeatedly? | The underlying hardware fault persists across reboots (not transient) |\n| **Why 5** | Why wasn't it caught earlier? | No proactive hardware health monitoring in place |\n\n---\n\n### 2. iFixit-Style Fixability Score\n\n**Score: 6/10** (Moderate Repairability)\n\n| Factor | Score | Rationale |\n|--------|-------|-----------|\n| **Diagnosis Difficulty** | 3/5 | Requires minidump analysis, stress testing, or hardware isolation |\n| **Parts Accessibility** | 4/5 | RAM, GPU, storage are user-replaceable; CPU/VRM harder |\n| **Software Fixes Available** | 4/5 | Driver updates, BIOS reset, Windows updates can resolve |\n| **Cost of Repair** | 4/5 | Most fixes are free (software) or low-cost (RAM reseat) |\n| **Documentation** | 3/5 | Extensive community guides, but no OEM diagnostic tool built-in |\n\n**Reliability Assessment:** HIGH confidence that this is fixable without replacement parts in ~70% of cases.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Fixability Verdict\n\n| Outcome | Probability |\n|---------|-------------|\n| **Software/driver fix** | ~35% |\n| **BIOS/config fix** (disable overclock, reset settings) | ~25% |\n| **RAM issue** (reseat/replace) | ~20% |\n| **CPU/MB failing** (requires replacement) | ~15% |\n| **PSU voltage instability** | ~5% |\n\n**Can you safely improve temperatures?** YES — monitoring temps is low-risk and won't stress components. Cleaning dust, improving airflow, and reapplying thermal paste are safe maintenance tasks.\n\n---\n\n### 4. PowerShell & Python Diagnostic Tools\n\n#### PowerShell (Built-in, No Install)\n\n```powershell\n# Get CPU temperature (Kelvin → Celsius conversion)\nGet-CimInstance MSAcpi_ThermalZoneTemperature -Namespace \"root/wmi\" | \n  Select-Object @{N='TempC';E={$_.CurrentTemperature / 10 - 273.15}}\n\n# Check recent BSOD events\nGet-WinEvent -FilterHashtable @{LogName='System'; Id=41} -MaxEvents 5 |\n  Select-Object TimeCreated, Message\n\n# View minidump files\nGet-ChildItem C:\\Windows\\Minidump -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue\n\n# System file integrity check\nsfc /scannow\n```\n\n#### Python (Requires: `pip install psutil HardwareMonitor`)\n\n```python\nimport psutil\nprint(f\"CPU Temp: {psutil.sensors_temperatures()['coretemp'][0].current}°C\")\nprint(f\"CPU Usage: {psutil.cpu_percent(interval=1)}%\")\n```\n\n#### Recommended External Tools (Non-stress)\n- **CrystalDiskInfo** — SSD/HDD health (free)\n- **HWiNFO** — comprehensive sensor readout (free, no stress test needed)\n- **Windows Memory Diagnostic** — built-in RAM check (reboot required)\n\n---\n\n### 5. Next Steps (Safe, No Stress Testing)\n\n1. Run `Get-WinEvent` to check if BSOD is tied to a specific driver\n2. Monitor temps with PowerShell above — flag anything >85°C\n3. Run `sfc /scannow` and `DISM /Online /Cleanup-Image /RestoreHealth`\n4. Check minidump files for the actual faulting module\n5. Reset BIOS to defaults if overclocking is enabled\n\nWant me to run any of these diagnostic commands on your system now?",
      "timestamp": 1783146338089
    },
